The issue is that between 10.352 and 11.159 is about 807ms, which is close to but under the 1000ms timeout. But then at 11.159 it goes to SAFE_IDLE. This suggests the sensor timeout check is happening.

But wait - when we send SENSE TURB 20, it should refresh the timestamp! Let me look at the uart_transport.c to see how it processes inputs:

Looking at uart_transport.c, in transport_apply_protocol_input:
```c
case CONTROLLER_INPUT_TURBIDITY:
    controller_input.kind = CONTROLLER_INPUT_TURBIDITY;
    controller_input.turbidity_ntu = protocol_input->turbidity_ntu;
    break;
```

And then it calls `controller_step(&s_transport_context.controller, controller_input)`. The controller_input has now_ms set from transport_now_ms() which is based on xTaskGetTickCount(). So each step should get a fresh timestamp.

But the issue is that in my controller_update_sensor_timeout function, I'm checking:
```c
if (controller->has_valid_turbidity) {
    uint32_t age_ms = now_ms - controller->last_turbidity_ms;
    if (age_ms > CONTROLLER_SENSOR_TIMEOUT_MS) {
        turbidity_stale = true;
    }
}
```

And then:
```c
if (turbidity_stale || level_stale) {
    controller_set_safe_idle(controller);
}
```

So if either sensor is stale, we go to SAFE_IDLE. But when we receive a new turbidity reading, we should refresh the timestamp BEFORE checking for timeout!

Let me look at the order of operations in my controller_step:
1. Call controller_update_sensor_timeout (checks for stale sensors)
2. Switch on input.kind
3. For TURBIDITY: update has_valid_turbidity, last_turbidity_ntu, last_turbidity_ms

Ah! The problem is the ORDER! I'm checking for sensor timeout BEFORE updating the timestamp with the new reading. So when we send a new SENSE TURB command after ~800ms, the old turbidity reading is still considered "valid" but it's almost 1000ms old. Then controller_update_sensor_timeout sees that the age is > 1000ms (because of accumulated time) and resets to SAFE_IDLE before we even process the new reading!

The fix is to update the timestamp BEFORE checking for timeout, or to only check for timeout when there's no new input. Let me fix this:

